      "id": "entry-004",
      "title": "Enemy Design Philosophy",
      "content": "## Design Pillars for Enemies\n\n### 1. Readable Intent\nEvery enemy telegraphs their next action. Players should never feel cheated by unexpected damage.\n\n### 2. Mechanical Identity\nEach enemy type has a clear mechanical hook:\n- **Void Wisps**: Weak alone, dangerous in groups\n- **Memory Eaters**: Steal cards temporarily\n- **Hollow Knights**: High block, telegraphed big attacks\n- **Corruption Spawn**: Spread debuffs, low HP\n\n### 3. Escalating Threat\nEnemies get more dangerous as fights drag on, encouraging aggressive play without being unfair.\n\n## Boss Design\n\nBosses are multi-phase encounters:\n\n**Phase 1**: Learn the patterns\n**Phase 2**: Patterns intensify, new mechanics\n**Phase 3**: Desperate final stand with unique abilities\n\nBosses should feel like puzzles to solve, not DPS checks.",
      "tags": ["design", "enemies", "balance"],
      "createdAt": "2026-01-20T11:00:00Z",
      "updatedAt": "2026-01-29T16:20:00Z"
    },
    {
      "id": "entry-005",
      "title": "Art Direction",
      "content": "## Visual Identity\n\n### Color Palette\n- **Primary**: Deep purples and void blacks\n- **Secondary**: Teal accents for UI elements\n- **Accent**: Gold for rewards/positive feedback\n- **Danger**: Crimson for damage/corruption\n\n### Style Keywords\n- Ethereal\n- Minimalist with detail bursts\n- Cosmic horror (subtle, not grotesque)\n- Memory/dream-like quality\n\n## UI Philosophy\n\n- Cards should feel weighty and satisfying to play\n- Information density without clutter\n- Particle effects for feedback, not decoration\n- Consistent iconography across all systems\n\n## Animation Priorities\n\n1. Card play animations (most visible)\n2. Enemy attack telegraphs\n3. Status effect applications\n4. Victory/defeat screens\n5. Meta-progression unlocks",
